<subSubSection id="C36265517A54FFD2FFCBF8C0FEADF87D" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC736DA7A54FFD2FFCBF8C0FEADF87D" blockId="23.[96,720,1795,2007]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
Similar to other peacock spiders in many respects, the genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="4C784D597A54FFD2FF5AF8E3FEB2F890" authorityName="Otto &amp; Hill" authorityYear="2017" box="[241,368,1824,1850]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Saratus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis id="B90CEAC87A54FFD2FF5AF8E3FEB2F890" box="[241,368,1824,1850]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">S. hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males and females are quite different. Emergent instars are boldly spotted and the deep blue or purple of the fan is based on layering of the cuticle rather than scale structure. The species name, 
<taxonomicName id="4C784D597A54FFD2FF1BF85DFED0F81D" authorityName="Otto &amp; Hill" authorityYear="2017" box="[176,274,1950,1975]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Saratus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis id="B90CEAC87A54FFD2FF1BF85DFED0F81D" box="[176,274,1950,1975]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">hesperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is based on the Greek name for the Evening Star (
<emphasis id="B90CEAC87A54FFD2FEABF87EFE9DF87C" box="[256,351,1981,2006]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Eσπερος</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
